emic =0Aliterature, ensuring the reliability (if not the interpretation) of=
 the =0Aunderlying findings,=E2=80=9D so I am perhaps not being quite fair;=
 perhaps the signals =0Areally work. But it=E2=80=99s delightful.=0A=0AAlso=
 it=E2=80=99s not just of academic interest. If you work at a quantitative =
hedge =0Afund and you find a good signal and your boss says =E2=80=9Cyes th=
is checks out =0Astatistically but I don=E2=80=99t feel good about trading =
it if we don=E2=80=99t have some =0Aexplanation that makes sense,=E2=80=9D =
you can just be like =E2=80=9Chang on I=E2=80=99ll be back to =0Ayou in 10 =
minutes=E2=80=9D and have ChatGPT generate the explanation.=0A=0A=0AThe Bit=
coin in a dump guy=0A=0AOne of the great financial innovators of our dumb a=
ge =E2=80=94 up there with Satoshi =0ANakamoto and Michael Saylor and Adam =
Aron =E2=80=94 is James Howells, whose innovation =0Awas (1) throwing a har=
d drive full of 8,000 Bitcoins [6]  <> into a garbage =0Adump in 2013 and (=
2) spending the last 12 years asking the local council to be =0Aallowed to =
dig up the dump and get it back. It is probably the most trenchant, =0Athe =
most earnest, and the highest-dollar-value piece of cryptocurrency =0Aperfo=
rmance art, which is saying something.=0A=0AWe talked about him back in 202=
1 <>, when he was going around saying =E2=80=9Che had =0Afinancial backing =
from a hedge fund to pay for the search so the council would =0Anot be out =
of pocket,=E2=80=9D andagain later that year <> when he was profiled in the=
 =0ANew Yorker <>. I wrote that he should securitize his more-or-less fanta=
stical =0Aclaim to get the Bitcoin back, but I guess he was having fun doin=
g what he was =0Adoing (persistently asking to dig up the dump).=0A=0AHere =
he is again <>:=0A=0AA judge has thrown out a man's attempt to sue a counci=
l to recover from a =0Arubbish tip a Bitcoin hard drive which he says is no=
w worth about =C2=A3600m.=0A=0AJames Howells had argued that his former par=
tner had mistakenly dumped the =0Ahard drive containing a Bitcoin wallet in=
 2013, and he wanted to access the =0Asite and recover the cryptocurrency.=
=0A=0ABut Newport council asked a High Court judge to strike out Mr Howells=
' legal =0Aaction to access the landfill or get =C2=A3495m in compensation.=
=0A=0AJudge Keyser KC said there were no "reasonable grounds" for bringing =
the claim =0Aand "no realistic prospect" of succeeding at a full trial.=0A=
=0AI love the idea that his claim is so valuable that, if they don=E2=80=99=
t let him dig =0Aup the dump, they should have to pay him =C2=A3495 million=
. What are the chances =0Ahe=E2=80=99d find the hard drive=3F (=E2=80=9CTh=
e landfill holds more than 1.4m tonnes of waste, =0Abut Mr Howells said he =
had narrowed the hard drive's location to an area =0Aconsisting of 100,000 =
tonnes.=E2=80=9D) Even if he did, what are the chances it=E2=80=99s in =0Ag=
ood enough shape that he can recover the Bitcoin=3F Does the hard drive eve=
n =0Abelong to him anymore=3F =E2=80=9CJames Goudie KC, for the council, ar=
gued that existing =0Alaws meant the hard drive had become its property whe=
n it entered the landfill =0Asite.=E2=80=9D It would be funny if the counci=
l dug up the dump and kept the Bitcoins =0Afor itself.=0A=0A=0AThings happe=
n=0A=0AUBS Close to Large Settlement Over Credit Suisse Tax Case <>. Bond m=
arket =E2=80=98=0Apolice <>=E2=80=99 are back as investors patrol spending =
plans. China steps up defence =0Aof renminbi <> against Wall Street bets. F=
TC=E2=80=99s Khan Urges Agency to =E2=80=98 Stay =0AAggressive <>=E2=80=99 =
After She Goes. UK Banknote Printer <> Gets Offer From Investors =0AWho Sou=
ght Stake. BlackRock private equity fund takes more than$600mn hit <> on =
