=80=98always fixed, every year <>,=E2=80=99 =0Abashes fellow contestants.=
=0A=0AIf you'd like to get Money Stuff in handy email form, right in your i=
nbox, =0Apleasesubscribe at this link <>. Or you can subscribe to Money Stu=
ff and other =0Agreat Bloomberg newslettershere <>. Thanks!=0A=0A[1] Or Byr=
ne Hobart has an explanation <> of =E2=80=9CWhat Does an =E2=80=98Analyst=
=E2=80=99 Do=3F=E2=80=9D that =0Ais in some ways a more sophisticated versi=
on of my crude one, including a =0Ahigher-order pooling of buy-side resourc=
es: =E2=80=9COne of the valuable services they =0Aprovide and which explain=
s why their research reports matter even if there are =0Abetter ways to mon=
etize stock-picking ability: part of a sell-side analyst's =0Ajob is to art=
iculate different flavors of the current buy-side consensus. A =0Astock pri=
ce only exists when a buyer thinks it's too cheap and a seller thinks =0Ait=
's too expensive, so there's always at least a bull case and a bear case. =
=0AWithin this, there can be fractal levels of detail: one bull case might =
be that =0Athis small growth company will end up beating a larger incumbent=
, while a =0Aseparate bull case might be that the same company will succeed=
 in selling =0Aitself to the incumbent. One cohort of bears might be concer=
ned that growth is =0Aslowing down, while another might be equally worried =
that management will =0Adestroy value by overpaying for growth. So buy-side=
 analysts talk to sell-side =0Aanalysts partly because other buy-side analy=
sts do; research quality ends up =0Abeing a Schelling Point for arranging e=
ven higher-quality discussions with =0Aopinionated, well-informed people on=
 either side of the argument. So the end =0Agoal of a sell-side analyst pub=
lishing a good report is not just to get =0Aopinions out there, but to soli=
cit other opinions, synthesize them, and =0Ahopefully get to the right answ=
er.=E2=80=9D=0A=0A[2] Except maybe for corporate access, if the index funds=
 want to talk to =0Atheir companies. (For instance, to lobby for environmen=
tal, social and =0Agovernance policies.)=0A=0A[3] That=E2=80=99s an exagger=
ation, and there are important quantitative signals built =0Afrom analyst r=
ecommendations, but probably not built from having long telephone =0Aconver=
sations with sell-side analysts about the details of their models.=0A=0A[4]=
 But not irrelevant. If your mandate is to understand a company really, =0A=
really well, one input to your understanding will be calling other people =
=E2=80=94 =0Alike sell-side research analysts =E2=80=94 whose job is to und=
erstand that company =0Awell. And see footnote 1, on the Schelling point ar=
gument for sell-side =0Aanalysts as coordinators of buy-side opinion.=0A=0A=
