ackground-color: #ccc;">How Analyst Job Cuts on Wall Street Are Reshaping E=
quity Research</a>=E2=80=9D:</p> <blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
The pandemic did, briefly, fuel a burst of hiring in equity research but wh=
en it faded, it left the same potent forces in place that have been gutting=
 the industry for years. Regulations on how banks charge for research, a sh=
rinking market for publicly listed companies, and the popularity of index-t=
racking funds have conspired to squeeze equity research in ways few could h=
ave imagined even a decade ago. Leaps in artificial intelligence only threa=
ten to accelerate that trend, with firms like JPMorgan already experimentin=
g with AI-powered analyst chatbots, sowing deeper doubts about the value of=
 fundamental analysis and whether investors will keep paying for it.</p> <p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Compared with their post-financial crisis peak, =
it=E2=80=99s estimated that the biggest banks globally have slashed the ran=
ks of equity analysts by over 30% to lows not seen in at least a decade. Th=
ose who remain often cover twice, or even three times, as many companies.</=
p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the pay, while still far higher than mo=
st jobs in industries outside finance, has stagnated. For example, starting=
 salaries for entry-level equity analysts currently range from $110,000-$17=
0,000 a year, barely above their levels before the financial crisis, accord=
ing to Vali Analytics. =E2=80=A6</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Despite a=
 small uptick in the first half of last year, spending on research globally=
 has sunk 50% since 2018, data from Substantive Research show. That year, M=
iFID II was enacted, forcing asset managers in the UK and European Union to=
 pay for research, rather than offering it for free as part of a suite of s=
ervices. US brokers supplying research to Europe-based managers also became=
 subject to the rule two years ago.</p> </blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Arguably this makes the market less efficient: If investors pool th=
eir resources to pay for research on every company, every company will be c=
overed, and investors will have access to research to help them understand,=
 and possibly invest in, every company. Without that, small companies might=
 be uninvestible: If you can=E2=80=99t get up to speed by reading a sell-si=
de report, and you can=E2=80=99t justify investing dozens of hours of your =
own time to understand each small company so you can pick a few good ones, =
you might just ignore the small companies. Rao, Tsekova and MacDonogh write=
:</p> <blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A growing body of evidence =
suggests stocks that fall off the sell-side radar often struggle to attract=
 investors, distorting valuations and making markets less efficient.</p> <p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One academic paper, which looked at data over a =
40-year period, showed how investors consistently over- or undervalued comp=
anies covered by fewer analysts. Another study found firms that had a decre=
ase in coverage showed a significant decline in investor recognition, incre=
asing their cost of capital. A third showed that low-coverage stocks traded=
 less and had wider bid-ask spreads, while =E2=80=9Corphaned=E2=80=9D compa=
nies were far more likely to be delisted.</p> </blockquote> <p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">I want to come back, though, to the last factor I mentioned a=
bove, the rise of online retail investors. Retail investors have historical=
ly been customers of sell-side research =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you have an accou=
nt at a big brokerage, that brokerage will probably give you access to some=
 research reports =E2=80=94=C2=A0but not particularly important ones. (They=
 probably don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>pay=C2=A0</em>for the research, and probab=
ly don=E2=80=99t have much access to direct phone conversations with the an=
alysts.) But the modern rise of retail investing has a =E2=80=9Cdo your own=
 research=E2=80=9D flavor, with investors spending a lot of time on Reddit =
and other social media sites rather than reading sell-side research.</p> <p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if bank sell-side research is on the decline=
, and social media-driven research is on the rise, there is an obvious real=
location of resources. Rao, Tsekova and MacDonogh=E2=80=99s story begins wi=
th Jerry Diao, a former sell-side analyst who now =E2=80=9Cplies his trade =
on social media=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cuntil recently =E2=80=A6 masqueraded =
his irreverent takes behind an avatar of Shrek.=E2=80=9D And:</p> <blockquo=
